'''''Asarum hartwegii''''' is a species of [[Asarum|wild ginger]] known by the common name '''Hartweg's wild ginger'''. 

It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[California]]; <ref>[http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=233500170 Flora of North America]</ref> It grows in forest habitat. This is a perennial herb growing from a [[ginger]]-scented [[rhizome]] which extends vertically deep into the ground. It forms a clump of elaborately white-veined leaves which are heart-shaped to round in shape and coated in curved hairs. Each is borne on a long [[Petiole (botany)|petiole]] up to 21 centimeters long. It bears a solitary flower near the ground on a short [[peduncle (botany)|peduncle]]. The flower has no petals but three curving, hairy, brownish or maroon [[sepal]]s which are whitish with red stripes on their inner surfaces. The fruit is a fleshy capsule containing many seeds.

